<font color="#FF0000">THE ROOTS OF PAIN-VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Thu May  8  1:12:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I think Robert Audrey's book, &quot;The Territorial Imperative&quot; gives all of us enhanced visibility to the sentiments and destruction caused by the Vietnam &quot;War&quot;.  His thesis is all living organisms have a defined territory; and, the organism-man in this case-will die in the defense of his territory.  I mean &quot;all&quot; living beings, from the lower cell organisms, up to and including man.  Ask yourself, &quot;Where is the territorial line for me; would it be W.W.I, W.W.II, Korea, Vietnam, when a drug crazed criminal breaks into your home and rapes your wife or threatens your children? Where do you draw the line that your territory as been violated severe enough to die in its defense?  In man this inborn instinct for an entire nation has been established starting with the Treaty of Westfalia in Europe centuries ago-at the birth of Nation States. Historically, what has happened is our two hundred year history of &quot;love of country,  patriotism, 'give me liberty or give me death, the American Flag'&quot; has harnessed this instinct to fight and die for ones country when asked to do so.  I see this thing called Patriotism as a sacred trust, a vital national resource for the survival of a nation, THE nation state, America.  The problems began when the trusted leadership at the very highest levels, I mean civilian levels, used this vital national resource to have our young men and some women fight and die without any commitment to win the war.  Essentially, if you fight and promise not to win you are wasting this precious blood and treasure, breaking the sacred trust bestowed to your own nation, your own government, and destroying the existing trust formations in many of our institutions and our values found in our history.  Just look at our history since Vietnam; it’s a mess.  This is what has happened.  Moreover, our young draftees faced incredible stress in not serving; and many of those who did because of the 200 years of Patriotic America--we just DON'T lose wars, had no concept we would not prosecute the war as we did in W.W.I and W.W.II, and no concept they would not be remembered as Heroes, Patriots and loved by Ma &amp; Pa and Apple Pie and the historian.  I mean, if you had told a young man at the start of the war that we are not going to really try and win; we just want them to give up; he would have looked at you with dismay and many more would not have permitted themselves to be conscripted to fight and die for their country.  You can begin to see the merits of Robert Audrey's thesis that man will die in the defense of HIS territory.  Trouble is we, the government, the media, and our history didn't tell us that the North Vietnamese ARE prepared to die in the defense of THEIR territory too; and, if you are not going to win, they will die in the defense of their territory, their nationstate; and, the North Vietnamese were a lot more committed than we ever were; and, below the verbal level, our people-America-never developed the commitment to die in the defense of their territory-America; it was not threatened.  I might add, because of this instinct, there is stress today for those who did not serve and there is stress for those who did serve.  I think Doc Spatz can tell us better than I can what people do to avoid stress.  I have seen it all around me for twenty five years since the Vietnam War.  What pains me is there is a guy who went way, way out on a limb to reestablish the cherished values that made our country great; and, our populous tries to destroy him.  Are we that reactive to authority figures?  Who is he? Can you guess?
